            <fr:title text="Commutator of matrices has no identity element">Commutator of matrices has no identity element</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The <fr:link href="/matrix-0029/" title="Commutator" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-0029/" display-uri="matrix-0029" type="local">Commutator</fr:link> of matrices over a <fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> (or a suitable <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">ring</fr:link>). It turns out, the commutator has no identity element. If it had one, say <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {E}]]></fr:tex>, then for any matrix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> we would have
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[\mathbf {E},\mathbf {A}]=\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>
and by anticommutativity of the commutator
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[\mathbf {A},\mathbf {E}]=-\mathbf {A}.]]></fr:tex>
But then we find the <fr:link href="/matrix-002A/" title="Jacobi Identity" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-002A/" display-uri="matrix-002A" type="local">Jacobi Identity</fr:link> fails to hold:
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[\mathbf {E},[\mathbf {B},\mathbf {C}]] + [\mathbf {B}, [\mathbf {C}, \mathbf {E}]] + [\mathbf {C}, [\mathbf {E}, \mathbf {B}]] = [\mathbf {C},\mathbf {B}]\neq 0.]]></fr:tex></html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
