            <fr:title text="Matrix commutator is not associative">Matrix commutator is not associative</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:li>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer. Then the set of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/matrix-0001/" title="matrix" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-0001/" display-uri="matrix-0001" type="local">matrices</fr:link> with entries in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> can be equipped with the <fr:link href="/matrix-0029/" title="Commutator" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-0029/" display-uri="matrix-0029" type="local">Commutator</fr:link> which is a binary operator denoted
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[A,B]=AB-BA]]></fr:tex>
for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrices <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. The commutator is not associative, i.e., in general we have
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[A, [B, C]] \neq  [[A,B],C]]]></fr:tex>
but it satisfies a variant called the <fr:link href="/matrix-002A/" title="Jacobi Identity" uri="http://localhost:8000/matrix-002A/" display-uri="matrix-002A" type="local">Jacobi Identity</fr:link>:
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[[A, [B, C]] + [B, [C, A]] + [C, [A, B]] = 0]]></fr:tex>
for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrices <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex>.</html:li>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
