            <fr:title text="Ring">Ring</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>A <html:dfn>(Unital) Ring</html:dfn> consists of a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> equipped with
<html:ul><html:li>an Abelian group structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(R,+,0)]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li>a multiplication <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\star \colon  R\times  R\to  R]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li>(Optional) a "one" element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1\in  R]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ul>
such that for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a,b,c\in  R]]></fr:tex>,
<html:ol><html:li>Associativity of addition: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a+(b+c)=(a+b)+c]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>Additive identity element: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a+0=0+a=a]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>Additive inverse: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a+(-a)=0]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>Commutativity of addition: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a+b=b+a]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>(Optional) Associativity of multiplication: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\star (b\star  c)=(a\star  b)\star  c]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>(Optional) Unital property (i.e., multiplicative identity element): <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\star 1=1\star  a=a]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>Left distributivity of multiplication over addition: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\star (b+c)=(a\star  b)+(a\star  c)]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li>Right distributivity of multiplication over addition <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a+b)\star  c=(a\star  c)+(b\star  c)]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
Some rings don't have a multiplicative unit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>, in which case they are "nonunital rings". If we don't care about the existence of the multiplicative unit, we'll just speak of "rings".</html:p><html:p>We also don't require all rings to be associative (i.e., multiplication may or may not be associative). When it matters, we will speak of "associative rings" and "nonassociative rings", but by default we will assume rings as associative.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>13</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>We could define a unital ring as an <fr:link href="/gr-000J/" title="Abelian group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-000J/" display-uri="gr-000J" type="local">Abelian group</fr:link> equipped with a monoid structure. The axioms for a unital ring would be satisfied automatically.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
